<DOC><DOCNO> AP880528-0180 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-88 2331EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-Refugees     05-28 0223</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Refugees,0230</SECOND><HEAD>Thailand Calls For Pressure, Repatriation of Vietnamese</HEAD><TEXT>   CHA-AM, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand on Saturday urged internationalpressure on Hanoi and the repatriation of Vietnamese fleeing theircountry who are determined to be migrants rather than refugees.   Participants at a conference on Vietnamese ``boat people'' alsocalled for more resettlement of refugees by third countries and anexpanded Orderly Departure Program from Vietnam to alleviate whatthey said was the ``gravest Indochinese refugee crisis since 1979.''   ``Pressure must be exerted by all concerned on Vietnam torecognize the humanitarian consequences of the (refugee) outflowand the negative image created for Vietnam,'' a senior Thai ForeignMinistry official, Pracha Guna-kasem, said at the conclusion of afour-day meeting.   The conference, sponsored by the Ford Foundation, broughttogether officials from the six countries of the Association ofSoutheast Asian Nations, as well as Hong Kong, the U.N. HighCommissioner for Refugees and observers from Japan, Sweden, UnitedStates, Australia and New Zealand.   The group's recommendations are to be submitted at a ASEAN-HongKong meeting in Bangkok this week.   The U.N. refugee commission said that it was handling about40,000 Vietnamese boat people in Asia as of March 31 this year, upfrom 32,000 the same period two years ago.   The largest numbers are found in Thailand, Malaysia, Hong Kong,the Philippines and Indonesia.</TEXT></DOC>